<FIRST>r a AM-LATeachers     05-21 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LA Teachers,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Awaits Negotiators For School District</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for the 22,000-member teachers'
union met again Sunday with school district representatives to seek
a solution to a week-old teacher walkout that has caused chaos in
city classrooms.
   Representatives of the Los Angeles Unified School District
arrived around 8:15 p.m., more than two hours after United
Teacher-Los Angeles negotiators showed up for talks set to begin at
6 p.m., said UTLA spokesman Catherine Carey.
   ``It looks like the other side is dragging its feet and trying
to prolong this thing,'' Ms. Carey said before they arrived. She
added that teachers were prepared for a second week in the walkout
that began May 15.
   ``We'll have our teachers out on the line again,'' she said.
``They've invested too much at this point.''
   Details of developments in recent talks have been sketchy
because of a news blackout imposed by state mediator Draz Mrvichin.
   The walkout last week played havoc with education in the nearly
600,000- student district. Many students walked out of classes and
some joined teachers on picket lines. In some cases, students were
housed in auditoriums because the district was unable to hire
enough substitute teachers to fill classrooms.
   During the 16-month-long labor dispute, teachers have sought
higher salaries and more say in how the district's 600-plus schools
are run.
   Teachers earn between $23,440 and $43,319 a year, depending on
experience and level of education. The union wants a three-year
contract with a 26 percent raise, including a 10 percent raise the
first year.
   The district, the second largest in the nation, has refused to
go higher than a 21.5 percent raise over three years.
   The strike, which began May 15, is the district's first since a
23-day walkout in 1970.
</TEXT>
