<FIRST>r a AM-RitualSlayings     05-21 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ritual Slayings,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Holds Quiet Funeral For Accused Cult Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Family members and a handful of friends attended
funeral services Sunday for the man authorities say was the
``godfather'' of a cult linked to at least 15 slayings on the
U.S.-Mexican border, a relative said.
   The body of Adolfo de Jesus Constanzo, 26, arrived in Miami late
Saturday night and was cremated for the funeral Sunday, Constanzo's
brother Fausto told WQBA radio in Miami.
   ``It was always his wish to be cremated,'' said Fausto
Constanzo, who said only that relatives and close friends were
invited to the funeral. He revealed no other details about the
services.
   ``It was a decision of ours to be so private,'' he said. ``We
don't want anyone there that doesn't belong there to curse the
funeral.''
   Constanzo has been described as the leader of a sect that
authorities blame for at least 15 killings outside the border city
of Matamoros. Sect members have said some slayings were ritual
killings while others were drug-related.
   Authorities had sought Constanzo and his female companion Sara
Aldrete Villarreal, 24, since the discovery of the first of the
bodies on a border ranch in April.
   Some bodies had been mutilated, with brains and organs removed.
   Aldrete and other sect members have said publicly that Constanzo
ordered his own execution and the killing of his right-hand man,
Martin Quintana Rodriguez, on May 6 when police moved in on their
Mexico City apartment earlier this month.
   An autopsy showed Constanzo died from multiple gunshot wounds to
the head and upper body.
</TEXT>
