<FIRST>u i BC-Britain-SovietExpulsions 1stLd-Writethru   05-21 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Soviet Expulsions, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0627,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Journalists, Diplomats Expelled From Britain, Soviet Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Moscow British Embassy comment,
identification of Britons, other details; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain ordered the expulsion of 11 Soviets, and
the Soviet Union responded by ordering eight British diplomats and
three journalists out of the country for alleged espionage, the
British Embassy said Sunday.
   ``It's a mirror-image act of retaliation,'' British Ambassador
Rodric Q. Braithwaite told a news conference.
   Roderic Lyne, the embassy's political counselor, said
Braithwaite was summoned to the Soviet Foreign Ministry on Saturday
night and told that 11 Britons would have to leave Moscow within 14
days.
   The previous day, Soviet Ambassador Leonid Zamyatin was called
to the British Foreign Office in London and told by Sir John
Fretwell, the deputy permanent undersecretary, that 11 Soviets were
engaged in ``activities incompatible with their status'' and must
leave in 14 days, a British Foreign Office spokesman said in London.
   The spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with British
custom, said Britain had not planned to make public the expulsions
and did so only after the Soviets retalitated.
   The spokesman refused to say what the Soviets were accused of
doing, but the charge he used of ``incompatible activities'' is
diplomatic jargon for espionage.
   Lyne said the Britons ordered expelled from Moscow were Embassy
Second Secretary Michael Anderson, Second Secretary Adam Noble,
Third Secretary Paul Sharp, Vice Consul Helen Pickering, Naval
Attache Capt. Christopher Meyer, Assistant Naval Attache Lt. Cmdr.
Christopher Watson, Assistant Military Attache Maj. Nigel
Shakespear and Warrant Officer Laing Purfit of the Defense Ministry
staff.
   Jeremy Harris of the British Broadcasting Corp., Ian
Glover-James of Independent Television News and Angus Roxburgh of
the Sunday Times of London also were give two weeks to leave the
Soviet Union, Lyne said.
   Roxburgh called the action ``ludicrous, almost too silly to
comment on.''
   The Foreign Office in London refused to identify the Soviets
expelled. Britain's ITN radio reported the Soviets were caught
spying on military installations.
   Press Association, the domestic British news agency, quoted
unidentified diplomats as saying those expelled from Britain
include Soviet journalists.
   The expulsions of British and Soviet nationals are the first
since the two countries expelled 31 of each other's citizens four
years ago.
   The 1985 dispute began when London ordered 25 Soviets to leave
after they were identified as secret agents by Soviet defector Oleg
Gordievsky.
   In addition to the 11 Britons ordered expelled Saturday, Lyne
said three British diplomats who had already completed their tours
of assignment in Moscow last year were declared ``persona non
grata'' by the Soviets, meaning they cannot return.
   Zamyatin also was told Friday that three former staff members at
the Soviet Embassy in London could not come back to Britain, Lyne
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
