<FIRST>u i BC-China 1stLd-Writethru   05-21 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0628,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Students Say Government Issues Ultimatum To Leave Square</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to ADD background, details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students occupying Tiananmen Square in violation
of martial law said Sunday Premier Li Peng ordered them to leave
the square by dawn Monday or face a military attack. Troops
occupied major state-run news organizations.
   Soldiers set up roadblocks around Beijing, presumably to prevent
more demonstrators from reaching the capital, and about 1,500
troops armed with automatic weapons moved into the train station.
   Troops occupied the People's Daily, Xinhua News Agency, the
Central Radio Station and the Central Television Station, a
People's Daily reporter said.
   Soldiers will be sent to major universities, which have been the
center of the monthlong protests for democratic change, to ``keep
order,'' Beijing television reported.
   Li called the 27th and 28th armies into the capital Friday night
and declared martial law in central Beijing on Saturday to put down
the student-led protests that have drawn hundreds of thousands of
people and caused major demonstrations in other cities. He did not
say how many troops were called in.
   Li, in a message to the independent student union that has led
the protests for a free press, an end to official corruption and
other reforms, said the military would clear Tiananmen by force by
5 a.m. Monday if the students refused to leave, according to an
announcement by the union.
   In a broadcast over the student loudspeaker system in the
square, they also claimed Li told Beijing jails to be ready to
accept a large number of students.
   ``We call on all of you to come stand with us,'' a student said
after the announcement. ``The students are very weak and they need
the people of Beijing to help them. Even 200,000 people cannot
withstand the army.''
   A Chinese source said 60,000 to 70,000 troops moved into the
city center by subway and followed connecting tunnels to the walled
palace, the history museum and the Great Hall of the People on
three sides of Tiananmen. The subway was closed to regular traffic
as of noon Saturday and remained closed Sunday.
   There was no outward sign of the reported troop presence and it
could not be confirmed.
   Official media repeatedly broadcast a statement that troops were
in Beijing to restore order, not to suppress the students. But it
was clear order could not be restored without moving the students
from Tiananmen.
   The widely ignored martial law regulations include bans on
marches, class boycotts, distribution of pamphlets, speeches, the
spreading of rumors, attacks on party, government or military
organs and ``any other destructive actions.''
   Li's hard-line stand toward the students appears to have forced
the resignation of the more liberal Communist Party General
Secretary Zhao Ziyang.
   Demonstrations in other cities continued Sunday.
   Tens of thousands of people marched in Shanghai, according to a
Western resident, and police diverted traffic. Several hundred
marched in the coastal city of Tianjin, a reporter at a local
newspaper said.
   The military failed to make an expected attack Saturday night on
200,000 students and supporters who kept all-night vigil in
Tiananmen Square. Many spent the night with gauze wound around
their mouths and noses for protection against a tear gas attack and
others slept on the hard stone pavement.
   Around the square and on roads citywide, citizens barricaded the
way to Tianamen with buses, trucks, lightposts and anything else
available.
   Thousands surrounded and immobilized tanks and trucks filled
with soldiers throughout the city and in the suburbs. Local
residents gave the soldiers cigarettes, food and water, and at one
point Sunday 600 soldiers retreated several hundred yards.
   Troops set up blockades on highways into Beijing to prevent more
people from moving into the capital.
   Crowds in Tiananmen and the surrounding area thinned
substantially Sunday, but people began flocking toward the square
in the evening after Li's ultimatum was announced.
</TEXT>
