<FIRST>r i AM-BRF-Taiwan-Premier     05-21 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF-Taiwan-Premier,0143</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Reportedly Approves Premier's Resignation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Lee Teng-hui on Sunday accepted
the resignation of Premier Yu Kuo-hwa after failing to persuade him
to remain in office, the official Central News Agency reported.
   Yu, 75, announced Wednesday he had submitted his resignation to
Lee to make way for a younger person and also to preserve unity
within the governing Nationalist Party.
   Yu, Taiwan's premier since 1984, has been criticized for his
cautious approach to economic and political reforms. Younger
members of the party consider him a liability in a December
parliamentary election.
   The CNA report made no mention of Yu's successor.
   But newspapers said earlier the probable candidate is Lee Huan,
72, the Nationalist Party's popular secretary-general. A decision
will be made at a meeting Wednesday of the policy-making central
committee, newspapers said.
</TEXT>
