<DOCNO> AP890521-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-89 1154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-PoweringDown Bjt   05-21 0959</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Powering Down, Bjt,920</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumers Urged to Use Electricity More Efficiently, Not Less</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In Virginia, you can earn a $4 monthly credit
on your electric bill by letting the utility cut power to your
water heater for a few hours a few times a month.
   In southern New Jersey, you can get a one-time cash rebate from
the utility of up to $619 for replacing your air conditioner with a
more efficient one.
   An Arizona utility offers to knock $75 off your bill if you put
a reflective film on your home's windows to block out the
ultraviolet rays of the desert sun.
   Across the country _ with some stark exceptions _ electric
utilities are pouring money into programs aimed at encouraging
energy efficiency and shifting the use of electricity from the peak
periods of demand to other times.
   ``There's a big move starting up,'' says Stephen Wiel, chairman
of the energy conservation committee of the National Association of
Regulatory Utility Commissioners.
   The main reason: Demands on the power supply system are growing
so rapidly that utilities are nearing the point of having to invest
in new sources of supply. The colossal failure of many past
investments in nuclear power plants is a powerful disincentive to
risk the billions needed for new construction.
   Virginia Power figures its program of interrupting power to
145,000 residential water heaters has saved it the need to add 150
megawatts of generating capacity _ the equivalent of a small power
plant, says spokesman Carl Baab.
   Utilities in some parts of the country have been tinkering with
electricity demand _ mainly to even out the daily and seasonal
peaks and valleys _ for several years. But the trend is now
accelerating as the utilities realize ``load management'' _ as it's
called in the business _ can mean more profits.
   Here's how: By encouraging customers to use less power in the
peak periods of summer and winter and to use more the rest of the
time, a utility can boost its overall electricity sales without
having to add to its maximum generating capacity.
   ``The reason we're doing this is that it's just good business,''
says Thomas Morron, a vice president of Edison Electric Institute,
an industry association.
   For consumers, these programs can mean lower electric bills. The
savings come not only from using more efficient appliances and
heating and cooling systems but also from avoiding the rate
increases that plant construction can bring.
   William McCollam Jr., president of Edison Electric, recently
estimated the number of utility-sponsored energy efficiency
programs had grown from 134 in 1977 to nearly 1,300 last year.
   He said this has allowed the industry to avoid adding 21,000
megawatts of new capacity over the past decade _ the equivalent of
about 21 large generating plants. A single plant that size would be
expected to cost at least $1 billion.
   After a decade of slow growth, electricity sales in the past two
years jumped by about 5 percent a year. Experts differ on the
outlook for future growth, but most agree demand could outstrip
supply in the 1990s unless new generating capacity is added.
   This is a key reason for the emphasis now on efficiency gains
and programs that can postpone the day when a utility must decide
how to supplement its power supply.
   The trend is not uniform, however. Some utilities have a surplus
of power and are aggressively peddling it.
   Ohio Edison Co. is offering financial incentives for natural gas
customers to convert their water heaters to electric and to buy
heaters that will run electric as well as on oil or gas.
   ``We're loaded with power; the idea is to sell it,'' said D.W.
Bettiker, coordinator of residential sales for Ohio Edison. ``We've
never had a conservation program.''
   Some of the utility programs are billed as conservation efforts,
but increasingly the term ``efficiency'' is substituted to reflect
the goal of stretching the use of each kilowatt-hour of power,
rather than eliminating some uses.
   ``One of the tough nuts to crack is the customer's perception
that conservation means deprivation,'' said Morron. ``Conservation
doesn't mean you have to put on a hair shirt and go live in a
cave.''
   Rather than being urged to turn down the thermostat in winter,
consumers are being told they can save money and still stay warm by
getting a more efficient heater.
   One of the most innovative utility programs is at Central Maine
Power. It hired an energy services company, Sesco Inc. of
Springfield, Mass., to make efficiency improvements in about 11,000
residences. Sesco pays for the improvements _ such as attic
insulation, window calking and lighting changes _ and the utility
pays Sesco for measurable reductions in each home's electricity use.
   The deal is set so the utility is assured of paying less for the
conservation than it would have paid to buy that amount of energy
from an outside supplier, or to build a new power plant to generate
the additional electricity. The utility customers pay nothing for
the efficiency improvements and are expected to save $2 million in
charges in the first year of the program.
   ``If all goes well, it's a win-win situation,'' said Frank
Chiaravalloti, a Central Maine spokesman.
   Although a growing number of utilities are starting or expanding
conservation and efficiency programs, some experts say regulatory
changes will be needed before the industry taps fully into the deep
reservoir of savings potential.
   The key problem from the utilities' viewpoint is that most state
regulatory agencies do not allow the industry to earn a profit on
their investment in conservation. They are allowed to recover the
cost, but no more. The result is that utilities may view increased
conservation as decreased profits.
</TEXT>
