<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-89 1157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-NewJerseyGovernor     05-21 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Jersey Governor,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eleven Vie To Succeed New Jersey's Popular Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight Republicans and three Democrats are
fighting in party primaries to emerge from the shadow of Gov.
Thomas H. Kean, widely credited with pumping pride into a state
that was long a favored target of standup comics.
   But Kean, a Republican who is barred by law from seeking a third
consecutive term, remains a central figure in the campaign,
especially among GOP candidates who vying to inherit his mantle.
   A millionaire from an old and influential New Jersey family,
Kean won office in 1981 by the narrowest margin in New Jersey
history, defeating Democratic Rep. James Florio by less than
one-twelfth of 1 percent of the vote.
   By 1985, his popularity had soared and he won a second term by
the widest margin in state history, getting 62 percent of the black
vote and widespread support among labor and Democrats.
   While the national Republican party grew more conservative under
Reagan, Kean advanced a moderate doctrine and urged the GOP to
bring women, blacks and other minorities into its fold.
   He rose to national prominence, delivering the keynote address
at the Republican National Convention last year and winning praise
from Presidents Reagan and Bush for his education initiatives.
   And he has been an unabashed New Jersey booster, appearing on
television commercials that tout the Garden State as an exciting
place to visit _ a novel thought for most Americans.
   His popularity in a state where Democrats far outnumber
Republicans makes him a tough act to follow.
   ``It's just like George Bush trying to succeed Ronald Reagan.
You have enormously huge shoes to fill,'' said Roger Stone, a
Washington-based consultant who is running Republican Rep. James
Courter's campaign.
   Stone said Kean was the first New Jersey governor to use
television to build a public image that reached beyond the state's
borders.
   Television is playing a crucial role in the primary, and
candidates are spending millions to broadcast their messages in the
nation's most expensive television markets.
   Although only about 400,000 members of each party are expected
to cast primary ballots, candidates will pour more than $7 million
into television advertising during the three weeks before the June
6 primary.
   When Kean took office, New Jersey staggered under economic
stagnation, high unemployment rates and serious budget problems.
   For most of his term, Kean rode an economic boom. He doubled the
size of the state budget during years when the treasury overflowed
with $1 billion surpluses.
   But the good times came to an abrupt halt before the primary
season. A predicted shortfall for next year grew to $500 million.
Some budget analysts believe the gap could be as wide as $700
million.
   Soaring auto insurance rates have dominated the primary race,
followed by debates over how to lower high local property tax rates
and whether state taxes should be increased to solve the budget
crisis.
   Growing traffic problems, congestion and the problems of
managing rapid growth in the nation's most densely populated state
also are big issues.
   Several of the candidates have likened themselves to Kean.
   Courter, former Attorney General Cary Edwards and Sen. William
Gormley are close Kean allies. Courter and Edwards use Kean's name
in slogans that appear below their ballot lines, calling themselves
``Tom Kean Republicans.''
   Gormley and Edwards are the most moderate candidates in the
race. Courter, Assembly Speaker Chuck Hadwick and Sen. Gerald
Cardinale have carved images as conservative Republicans.
   Among the Democrats, Florio, author of the federal Superfund
law, is widely considered the virtually unbeatable frontrunner. Now
in his third bid for the statehouse, he has run a low profile
campaign, drawing criticism from his opponents for remaining silent
on many key issues.
   In spite of the stacked political odds, liberal Assemblyman Alan
Karcher and Princeton Mayor Barbara Boggs Sigmund, daughter of Rep.
Lindy Boggs, D-La., and the late Hale Boggs, are running spirited
Democratic campaigns.
   Three other Republicans are running low-budget campaigns. They
are former state tourism official Lois Rand, retired Coast Guard
Capt. Thomas Blomquist and James A. Kolyer, an industrial arts
teacher from Matawan.
</TEXT>
