<FIRST>u w AM-Coelho-Dairy Bjt   05-21 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coelho-Dairy, Bjt,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Democrat Had Dairy Industry Investment While Pushing Dairy
Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Tony Coelho owned an interest in a dairy
management company at the same time he was pushing legislation to
help maintain the profitability of some dairy farms, a review of
records shows.
   Coelho, the House majority whip and third-ranking Democrat in
the chamber, became a limited partner in Dairy Management
Associates in December 1983, according to his financial disclosure
forms.
   When he bought into the partnership with an investment valued at
between $5,000 and $15,000, the California congressman was a member
of the House livestock, dairy and poultry subcommittee. He became
chairman in 1985, a position he held for two years during the time
the controversial 1985 farm bill was passed.
   Coelho's financial dealings have been the subject of public
interest since recent disclosures that a California savings and
loan official purchased a $100,000 bond for Coelho when the
congressman was unable to come up with the money.
   Dairy Management Associates developed a computer software
program for managing dairy herds, allowing farmers to determine
things such as how much milk a cow produces and how much it eats,
Coelho's aides said. The program also is used by veterinarians.
   Fred Hatfield, a Coelho aide, said the congressman was
``comfortable enough in his mind to realize there was no potential
for anything that he dairy or agriculture committee was going to
pass that was going to impact directly on that investment.''
   No law or rule prevents members of Congress from holding assets
that might conflict with their official duties. They are free to
craft and vote on legislation that could affect their financial
interests.
   White House officials and other executive branch employees, on
the other hand, are barred under the basic federal conflict of
interest law from taking government action in which they or their
immediate family has a financial interest unless they obtain a
waiver. The top penalty is two years in prison and a $10,000 fine.
   In 1985, Coelho and then-Rep. James Jeffords, R-Vt., introduced
a bill that, among other things, would pay farmers not to produce
milk at a time the industry was beset with surpluses.
   The legislation, which drew the ire of consumer and milk-user
groups, was described by Coelho as a way to ease some producers out
of dairying while retaining profitability for the rest.
   Ultimately, Congress passed legislation that called for modest
cuts in the price support program, but authorized federally
subsidized buy-outs of entire dairy herds.
   Ellen Haas of Public Voice, a self-styled consumer lobby who
fought Coelho on dairy price support measures in 1985, said it
stood to reason that if dairy farmers stay healthy they might be
able to afford to buy computer software programs to manage herds.
She said she had no idea of Coelho's investment at the time.
   One argument for exempting Congress from conflict-of-interest
statutes is that lawmakers must publicly disclose their holdings so
voters can decide whether an official is acting for personal
enrichment.
   Coelho listed his holding as Dairy Management Associates in 1983.
   In four following years, the entry was less descriptive. He
simply stated on his financial disclosure forms that he had an
interest in ``DMA (a California limited partnership).''
   Coelho put his assets, including his DMA interest, in a blind
trust last June.
   Hatfield said Coelho does not fill out his forms personally and
speculated that an aide called the company by its acronym, a
pattern repeated annually.
   Partnership records on file in California _ the most recent was
Jan. 18, 1985 _ show Coelho's general partner in Dairy Management
Associates was Samuel A. Nash, who formerly worked for Coelho's
accountant. The company address was the same as the accountant's
office in Merced, Calif.
   Hatfield, Coelho's aide, said the congressman knew Nash, but not
well. He said Dairy Management Associates has not had an office for
several years.
   Another limited partner in Dairy Management is John Mack, the
former aide to House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas. Mack, a close
friend of Coelho's, resigned last week after an outpouring of
criticism over a newspaper story detailing his attack on a woman in
1973.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
