<FIRST>r w AM-AIDSDrugs     05-21 0931</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Drugs,890</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grassroots Concept Gaining Momentum in AIDS Drug Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A novel, grassroots concept in drug testing
pioneered by AIDS victims and their doctors is gaining momentum and
soon may see its first victory with widely expected government
approval of a treatment for a lethal AIDS-related pneumonia.
   Far from the ivory towers of academic medical centers, the
testing is being conducted in a few inner cities hard hit by the
disease where local AIDS doctors and their patients search together
to find treatments that work and disgard those that don't.
   These community programs _ the two major ones are in New York
and San Francisco _ were begun by AIDS patients and physicians
frustrated by the slow pace of academic and government research to
turn out a cure for acquired immune deficiency syndrome and its
deadly complications.
   ``People with AIDS just decided to do it themselves,'' said
Thomas Hannon, associate director of the Community Research
Initiative, which operates out of an old loft building in New York
where participating doctors administer experimental therapies to
AIDS patients.
   Research data gathered by the New York group and the County
Community Consortium in San Francisco on an aerosol version of the
drug pentamidine pursuaded a Food and Drug Administration advisory
committee earlier this month to recommend approval of the treatment
to prevent pneumocystis carinii pneumonia. The lung ailment kills
60 percent of all AIDS victims.
   The FDA is widely expected to approve aerosol-administered
pentamidine shortly.
   Pentamidine was approved by the FDA as an injectable drug five
years ago to treat those already suffering from pneumocystis. Many
doctors, though, administered it as a spray. In February, the FDA
expanded pentamidine's use in aerosol form as an experimental
medication under government review.
   As a spray, the drug is delivered directly into the lungs where
the pneumonia infection first shows up. In this form, pentamidine
has been shown to help prevent pneumocystis infection.
   Advocates of the grassroots programs say the FDA advisory
committee's action represents a major breakthrough for the concept
of community-based research and recognition that primary-care
doctors can produce solid, clinical data in the routine delivery of
medical services to their patients.
   The result, they hope, will be to help get effective therapies
to AIDS victims faster. Community programs reach more people, they
say, and so will be able to bring more AIDS patients into clinical
trials, and with more participation, there will be more information
with which to assess the effectiveness of drugs.
   The concept has won the backing of many scientists, drug
companies and the federal government, which is preparing to award
$6 million in grants to develop community-based research programs
throughout the country. In addition to the federal money, the
American Foundation for AIDS Research in April gave $1.4 million to
16 community organizations starting reseach programs.
   Dr. Burton Lee _ a cancer researcher, member of former President
Reagan's AIDS commission and now President Bush's personal
physician _ avidly supports community-based research as an
extension of the work going on in university and government centers.
   These programs, he said, are free of the ``inherent biases'' of
academic studies to exclude the sickest patients. A more
representative sampling, which community programs provide, produces
better results and without any slippage in quality, since many
academic researchers sit on the advisory boards of the community
programs, he said.
   He credits AIDS activists for pointing out the weaknesses in
traditional research. ``The communities have stepped up to bat and
they have tried to speed up the system. They came up with a
constructive idea and I think it's a good one,'' Lee said.
   He added: ``I hope they (community-research programs) spread out
into other diseases. I think it's an excellent model for testing
cancer drugs, diabetes drugs, heart disease drugs and others.''
   Martin Delaney, co-founder of Project Inform, a San
Francisco-based AIDS education group, was an early proponent of
community-based research and still supports it, but he says the
movement has been ``romanticized.''
   Few clinical trials are being done by community groups other
than those in New York and San Francisco, and most of the efforts
are spearheaded by doctors _ not AIDS patients _ and so are not
really the symbols of patient empowerment that advocates describe
them to be, he said.
   ``It's an important part of a broader puzzle,'' Delaney said.
``I don't think it's ever going to replace university-based
research, and there's a limit to how big it can get because of the
time it takes for doctors to participate.''
   One mistake AIDS activists have made is in equating research
with treatment, he said.
   ``The more pressure we put on the research process as being a
way for treatment, the more we confound the research process, and
the politicians find it a nice easy way out, instead of providing
the money for health care,'' Delaney said.
   Yet, the movement is generating ``overwhelming'' interest, said
Lawrence Deyton, assistant director for community research at the
National Institute for Allergy and Infectious Diseases.
   When the government announced its $6 million program, it got
more than 700 requests for information about it. Deyton declined to
say how many applied by the April deadline, but a Capitol Hill
source who spoke on the condition of anonymity said it was more
than 60.
   Deyton estimated that as many as a dozen community-based groups
are now involved in clinical trials for AIDS therapies.
   With more trials, he said, there would likely be more
participation by Hispanics, blacks, intravenous drug users and
women, who are now underrepresented in clinical testing.
</TEXT>
