<FIRST>r i AM-Japan     05-21 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ishida Elected Head of No. 2 Opposition Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's second-largest opposition party elected a
new chairman Sunday to succeed the party leader who resigned in an
influence-peddling scandal.
   Koshiro Ishida, the Komeito Party's new leader, told members,
``I will fight to make the Komeito once more a party that is clean
and trustworthy.''
   Ishida, 58, previously one of four party vice chairmen, was
elected to succeed Junya Yano, who resigned last week when
prosecutors began formal questioning of a Komeito member of
Parliament.
   Katsuya Ikeda of Komeito and Takeo Fujinami of the governing
Liberal Democratic Party were interrogated by police last week.
They are suspected of taking bribes from Recruit Co., an
information and publishing conglomerate.
   The so-called Recruit scandal has resulted in 14 bureaucrats and
businessmen being arrested on bribery and securities law violation
charges.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, who has acknowledged receiving
political contributions from Recruit, announced last month he was
resigning to take responsibility for the scandal. But his party has
yet to find a successor who commands widespread respect and is
untainted by the scandal.
   Yano himself was under fire in Komeito, the second-largest
opposition party after the Socialists, for links to an earlier
insider-trading scandal.
   More than 600 party members, including 56 members of the
512-seat House of Representatives and 23 members of the 252-seat
House of Councilors, attended the special party convention in
downtown Tokyo.
   Ishida urged fellow party members to reflect on a ``lack of
seriousness'' among members of Parliament. The new party leaders,
he said, must examine the scandal and reform the party.
   ``I believe this is the way to win public confidence,'' he said.
   Though as an opposition legislator Ikeda had no official power,
he repeatedly lodged questions in Parliament that prosecutors saw
as helpful to Recruit, and he gained financial benefits from
Recruit share transactions.
   Recruit sold bargain-priced, unlisted shares in a subsidiary to
about 160 influential politicians, aides, bureaucrats and
businessmen, allegedly in an attempt to gain influence in the
government. When public trading in the shares began, their prices
soared and buyers made large profits.
   Ishida was first elected to the House of Representatives in 1967.
</TEXT>
