<FIRST>r a AM-Diver'sParents     05-21 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Diver's Parents,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parents of Slain Navy Diver Return Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT TOBACCO, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard and Patricia Stethem have
finally come home after nearly a year in West Germany, now that a
man has been convicted and sentenced to life in prison for the 1985
terrorist murder of their son.
   Robert Stethem, 23, a Navy diver, was shot and his body dumped
onto the pavement at Beirut International Airport during the 17-day
hijacking of TWA Flight 847.
   The Stethems, both 53, attended 65 court sessions in Frankfurt,
West Germany, beginning last July, for the trial of Muhammad Ali
Hammadi. ``Nearly a year out of my grandchildren's lives,'' Mrs.
Stethem said.
   The Stethems returned to their Charles County home Thursday
night after Hammadi's sentencing.
   ``We're very confident and really feel he'll stay behind bars,''
Mrs. Stethem said of Hammadi. ``So we feel our trip was worth it.''
   ``They say time heals all wounds,'' Stethem said. ``The pain
hasn't healed yet. And I don't see it happening at this point. But
this verdict has helped a lot.''
   The first order of business was working in their yard and
tending the rose garden Mrs. Stethem maintains to harvest flowers
for her son's grave at Arlington National Cemetery.
   A neighbor mowed the lawn while the Stethems were away, but a
three-week lapse and abundant rain have given it time to grow
knee-high.
   ``We must get on with our lives now,'' said Stethem, a civilian
Navy employee. ``We don't feel in any danger. We've been victims
already ... We'll never have Rob back.''
   In the garage is their son's car, with a vanity license plate
Stethem obtained after his son was killed. ``ROBBIES,'' it says.
   ``We don't drive it much,'' Stethem said.
   The elder Stethem joined the Navy in 1953 when he was 17. He
retired in 1979 but later returned as a civilian employee.
   Mrs. Stethem also was in the Navy, in California, when they met.
She now is a secretary at the U.S. Court of Military Appeals in
Washington.
   There are three other children: Cheryl, 31, a mother of two, and
two Navy sons, Kenneth, 29, and Patrick, 23. ``I had actually tried
to talk all of them into joining the Air Force,'' their father said.
   When the TWA airplane was hijacked in June 1985, Robert Stethem
was part of a crew of Navy divers returning from a routine
maintenance job at a U.S. Navy sewage treatment plant in Greece.
They were on their way back to Little Creek, Va., where Patrick
Stethem now holds the same job his brother did.
   Why Stethem was chosen for execution by the Shiite Moslem
terrorists remains unknown. Another diver, severely beaten at the
same time, lived to testify at Hammadi's trial. Two terrorists
involved in the hijacking remain at large.
   Although the time they spent at the trial in Germany did not
provide answers to all their questions, the Stethems derived a
certain solace. ``I had to be there,'' Ms. Stethem said. ``I had to
know what was happening. I would've climbed the walls wondering
what was happening if I stayed at home.''
   During breaks in the trial, she did volunteer work, typing at
the dental clinic of the U.S. military base where they stayed. ``A
lot of nights, I didn't sleep and walked around and called my
daughter'' in Maryland, she said. Her husband said he read a lot of
books about terrorism.
   A security detail whisked them into the courtroom, which was
inside a prison, and they sat with the prosecutor behind
bulletproof glass. An interpreter translated.
   Now that they're home, the Stethems plan to visit their son's
grave, taking newly cut roses from the garden and news of what
happened to Hammadi.
   ``This is going to be great, going this time,'' Mrs. Stethem
said, ``because I can tell him we just got one.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
