<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-89 1254EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-VirginiaPrimary     05-21 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Virginia Primary,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Square Off In Virginia Statehouse GOP Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three candidates are running in Virginia's
first Republican gubernatorial primary in 40 years, vying for the
chance to oppose Lt. Gov. L. Douglas Wilder in his bid to be the
nation's first elected black governor.
   Virginia Republicans, eager for victory after two straight
shutouts for the statehouse, hold a primary June 13 in hopes of
stirring more voter interest than a convention would attract.
   ``I don't see any signs that the gamble is paying off,'' said
Mark J. Rozell, a political science professor at Mary Washington
College in Fredericksburg.
   The state party chairman disagrees.
   ``I think we're dominating the news,'' said state Republican
Chairman Donald W. Huffman. ``We're getting noticed, and that's
what it's all about.'' The three candidates have held 11 public
debates that have garnered statewide attention, the last one
Wednesday.
   On the Democratic side, Wilder is unchallenged for the
nomination, with selection set for the party convention June 9 and
10. By law, Democratic Gov. Gerald L. Baliles cannot serve a second
consecutive term.
   The Republican primary candidates are:
   _ Former state Attorney General J. Marshall Coleman, 46, who
lost to Democrat Charles Robb in 1981, was squeezed out when he
started talking about another bid for governor in 1985 and then
sought but failed to get the nomination for lieutenant governor.
   _ Rep. Stanford E. Parris, 59, is a former state legislator who
touts his experience in state and federal office. An unsuccessful
contender for the gubernatorial nomination in 1985, he never has
run in a statewide race.
   _ Former Sen. Paul S. Trible Jr., 42, who did not seek
re-election to his U.S. Senate seat last year. Trible is the
front-runner in the contest, according to polls, but his lead may
be narrowing. Parris and Coleman say Trible gave up his seat rather
than face Robb, who won in a landslide over a little-known
candidate.
   All three stress the goals of boosting education and fighting
drugs. Coleman has issued a blanket pledge not to raise taxes.
Parris said he can't rule out any tax increase in four years.
Trible has refused to make a no-tax pledge.
   The polls show Trible favored in a head-to-head contest with
Wilder, who won the state's No. 2 office in 1985 with 52 percent of
the vote. Coleman is about even with Wilder, and Parris trails the
Democrat.
   Republican national chairman Lee Atwater has made the Virginia
gubernatorial campaign a key test for the GOP. ``I'm going to come
down here every week if I have to and do everything I can,''
Atwater said at a Virginia Beach fund-raiser earlier this month.
   President Bush carried the state last year with 60 percent of
the vote. Democrats have captured Virginia's electoral votes only
twice since the end of World War II _ in 1948 and 1964.
   State Republicans last tried a gubernatorial primary 40 years
ago. The most successful primaries for the GOP have been those
conducted by the opposition.
   In 1969, a three-way Democratic primary badly split the party
and led to the election of Virginia's first Republican governor
since Reconstruction, Linwood Holton.
   In 1977, another Democratic primary set up a Republican victory
when former Lt. Gov. Henry E. Howell staged an upset victory over
Attorney General Andrew P. Miller in June. Howell lost that fall to
Republican John N. Dalton.
   After 1977, the Democrats stopped holding primaries and started
winning elections _ in 1981 with Charles S. Robb and 1985 with
Gerald L. Baliles.
   ``When the Democrats quit the primary, a Democrat got elected,''
Rozell said. ``I think there's a connection there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
