<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-TrainCrash     05-21 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Train Crash,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Train Collision in Soviet Central Asia Causes Giant Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two freight trains, one laden with propane,
collided in Soviet Central Asia, causing a fire and explosion that
destroyed factories and 13 houses and killed an unspecified number
of people, Tass reported Sunday.
   The official Soviet news agency said the trains collided while
being switched from one track to another on approach lines to a
station in Alma Ata, the capital of the republic of Kazakhstan,
1,800 miles southeast of Moscow.
   ``A huge fire which broke out as a result of the collision
caused a powerful explosion which claimed human lives,'' Tass said.
   It did not say how many people died or how many factories were
destroyed in the accident Saturday night. The news agency said,
``Measures are being taken to help the people and eliminate the
collision's consequences.''
   A commission has been set up to investigate the cause of the
accident.
