<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-89 1324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-People     05-21 0826</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0861</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44, PAN1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANNES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American actor Mickey Rourke, at the
center of a controversy over comments he made at the Cannes Film
Festival last week, denied Sunday that he ever gave money to the
Irish Republican Army.
   Rourke was denounced by British lawmakers after a news
conference Friday called to promote his latest movie,
``Francesco,'' in which he plays St. Francis of Assisi.
   Asked then if he ever donated money to religious causes, Rourke
replied, ``Yes I have, to causes in Northern Ireland. Yes, to Joe
Doherty, who is a prisoner in New York City.''
   Doherty, 33, was convicted of the murder of a British Army
captain and sentenced to life in prison in 1981. He escaped from
prison, but was captured by the FBI in 1983 and jailed in New York.
   Rourke issued a statement Sunday through a spokesman saying he
had been involved only in humanitarian aid in Northern Ireland,
never with the Irish Republican Army.
   If people in England ``choose to use this as a platform to
persecute me as an Irish Catholic American, then that is their
indulgence,'' he said.
   O'Rourke has starred in ``Angel Heart,'' ``Barfly'' and ``The
Pope of Greenwich Village.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comic Jay Leno was made an honorary member of
the University of Nevada-Reno's Class of `89 after taking humerous
jabs at members.
   Leno addressed about 1,000 seniors Friday at a graduation lunch.
   To an art major, Leno quipped: ``Art?! So you want to live at
home with your parents when you get out.''
   To a psychology major, he said: ``Oh _ so when you're out of a
job, you'll know why.''
   When a sociology major said he was unsure what he wanted to
pursue after graduation, Leno turned to the audience and said: ``It
is hard to believe the Japanese are ahead of us.''
   Leno was given a silver buckle, a school tie, a plaque making
him an honorary member of the Class of `89 and a bag of tortilla
chips.
   Leno, a frequent ``Tonight Show'' host who does commercials for
tortilla chips, is making a weekend appearance at Harrah's Tahoe.
He's a 1972 graduate of Emerson College in Boston.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Brokaw admitted he
was in the position of a ``huckleberry in the path of a hungry
grizzly.''
   But the NBC-TV news anchor went ahead anyway and defended news
coverage of last summer's Yellowstone fires to a group of park
activists.
   ``As trying as it was, I am confident the daily news readers and
viewers had an accurate view of the fires,'' Brokaw said Saturday
of the flames that raged over nearly half of Yellowstone's 2.2
million acres.
   Brokaw's speech came near the end of the two-day conference of
the Greater Yellowstone Coalition, during which nearly every
speaker complained that the news media gave the impression that the
country's first national park was destroyed by the flames.
   ``Taken one at a time, some stories may be flawed,'' Brokaw
conceded. ``But no American news reader or watcher makes a judgment
based on one story. News as we consume it is a steady diet.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 26-year-old television journalist resigned
after management learned she was the subject of a nude photo
feature in the July issue of Playboy magazine, which hits
newsstands this week.
   Shelly Jamison, a news producer, reporter and fill-in anchor is
on the cover of the magazine with her clothes on, and on the inside
with them off.
   ``If they don't fire me, I'll probably quit anyway,'' she told
the Arizona Republic earlier in the week.
   Jamieson has an unlisted telephone and could not be reached for
comment on Sunday.
   KTST-TV News Director Dave Howell said in a prepared statement
Friday that she had resigned, effective immediately.
   ``Neither the article in the July issue of Playboy magazine nor
the use of KTSP-TV trademarks nor the pictures taken on the
premises were done with our authorization, knowledge or
permission,'' the statement said.
   Jamison told Playboy: ``Instead of being a reporter, for once I
felt like being the subject.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC sportscaster Dick Enberg, who began
his announcing career when he answered a campus newspaper
advertisement 31 years ago, returned to Indiana University to honor
his mentor.
   Enberg, who earned his doctorate at IU in 1962, remembered when
he and retiring broadcast journalism professor Richard Yoakam
handled the first radio broadcast of the Little 500 bicycle race.
   Enberg and Yoakam at one point realized that ``we had no
material left and we had three hours to go.'' Enberg said the
incident taught him his most important broadcast lesson _ be
prepared.
   Enberg, who has won four Emmys and covers everything except
golf, bowling and auto racing, said his favorite sport is baseball.
   It is also the hardest to announce, he said, because the pace is
slow compared to football and basketball.
