<FIRST>u a AM-PrisonProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0647 05-21 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0647,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Town Vows To Continue Prison Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `The 240-bed ..., to CORRECT spelling of Pepe,
sted Pep. Pick up 7th graf, `The second ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BRAINTREE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Massachusetts flag now flutters
over a former boarding school seized last week by state officials
who plan to make it a prison.
   But on trees nearby are tacked homemade signs depicting a cow in
prison stripes and one word: ``Never.'' And there is still talk at
the general store of stopping the state from building a 500-inmate
medium-security prison in this isolated town of 800 people and more
than twice as many dairy cows.
   It all started in 1983, when the Pioneer Valley Academy shut its
doors and state officials decided to turn the building into a
prison for drunken drivers. The project didn't go through and the
prison was built instead in Springfield, 40 miles away, but that
wasn't the end of the story.
   ``They came back with the regular prison,'' said Dorothea
Thomas-Vitrac, chairwoman of the town Board of Selectmen.
   To the state, the former Seventh Day Adventist boarding school
perched on a windswept ridge is a place to build a badly needed
prison without having to start from scratch.
   The 240-bed first phase of the prison, which the state hopes to
complete in 18 months, is expected to cost about $25.6 million,
including renovations at the school, said Louise Pepe, spokeswoman
for the state Division of Capitol Planning.
   The second construction phase is expected to cost $20.4 million,
Pepe said.
   For the townspeople it's a battle to preserve the rural way of
life in this little one-store hamlet, where the road in front of
Town Hall is blocked for 20 minutes twice a day while a farming
family moves its cows to and from the barn for milking.
   It's the sort of place where the main road is a country lane
squeezed between stone fences marking pastures that were cleared
when the nation was young. Where the town crew waits for the snow
to stop before plowing, even if it takes days.
   ``We don't sit down and strategize how we are going to convince
people we will be good neighbors, but we will be talking with
them,'' said Deodato Arruda, a spokesman for the state Department
of Corrections.
   She said eight armed corrections officers would be stationed at
the prison around the clock.
   But Susan Reed, co-owner of the general store and president of a
citizens group fighting the prison, said the locals will not be won
over.
   ``I don't think there is any chance of that happening,'' she
said. ``They haven't dealt with us fairly at any time in the past
three years.''
   The town appropriated $100,000 last year _ one-fifth its budget
_ to fight the prison. Two lawsuits challenging the site-selection
process are pending in the courts.
   The owners of the school property also are fighting back,
promising to challenge the eminent-domain process by which the
state seized the property. They say the $5.25 million pricetag the
state has placed on the 730-acre property is not nearly enough.
   Walpole real estate developer Daniel E. Stiar bought the academy
with Newton psychiatrist Gary Jacobsen in 1985 for $3.2 million.
The men had hopes of turning it into a psychiatric hospital, but a
year later they offered it to the state for $10 million.
   ``I wish I had never bought the property. It's been a lot of
aggravation,'' he said.
   The state Inspector General blasted the state's handling of the
matter in a report. He suggested that bumbling alone delayed the
prison at least 18 months and, in some cases, exacerbated the
controversy.
   Inspector General Joseph Baressi said an environmental study
that was to have cost $75,000 ended up costing $645,000. The town
has charged in a lawsuit that the report did not adequately address
environmental issues.
</TEXT>
