<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-89 1350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Missiles     05-21 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Missiles,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says Rift Remains In Missile Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Sunday said it is
still dissatisfied with a U.S. plan for solving a NATO rift over
whether to hold superpower talks on short-range nuclear missiles.
   But government spokesman Hans Klein told reporters that West
Germany was confident the issue can be resolved before a May 29
NATO summit in Brussels.
   Referring to the U.S. compromise proposal brought back by
Defense Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg after a visit Friday to
Washington, Klein said: ``I think it forms the basis for a
solution, but a solution has not yet been found.
   ``The discussions are continuing,'' Klein said.
   He declined comment on what obstacles remained.
   Klein said that Chancellor Helmut Kohl would send President Bush
a letter detailing the government's position on Monday and that
Kohl would call Bush and other NATO leaders to discuss the matter
in coming days.
   Klein briefed reporters after Kohl met for two hours with
Stoltenberg and Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher.
   West Germany has been pressing for prompt superpower talks on
the missiles. The Bush administration orginally had flatly rejected
such talks.
   The disagreement has caused NATO members to choose sides in the
dispute and clouded plans for the NATO summit.
   Under the U.S. compromise plan, negotiations on short-range
nuclear weapons would be linked at some indefinite point to talks
now under way in Vienna designed to reduce conventional forces,
such as tanks.
   The short-range talks would not be held until the Soviet-led
Warsaw Pact agreed to sizable reductions in its conventional
forces, which Washington says far outnumber NATO forces.
   Acceptance of short-range negotiations at all represents a major
concession by Bush. For months, U.S. officials had ruled out any
negotiations on the missiles, saying they were essential to the
defense of Western Europe.
   In return, the U.S. wants West Germany to relent in its demands
for ``speedy'' negotiations and state firmly that it rejects the
immediate elimination of short-range weapons.
   Government sources in Bonn, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the obstacles to agreement centered on the latter provision,
the so-called ``third zero option'' under which short-range
missiles would be immediately scrapped.
   U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III said the U.S.
counterproposal also envisioned postponing until 1992 a decision on
deployment and production of missiles that are faster and travel
farther than the Lance missiles.
   Amid a wave of disarmament feeling in West Germany, Bonn has
resisted a plan to upgrade the U.S.-made Lance missiles deployed in
West Germany against the Soviet-led forces.
   Kohl wants to delay any decision to deploy the new missiles
until at least 1992, after next year's national elections.
   All major West German political parties are united in the demand
for negotiations out of concern their country is the likeliest
battlefield in the event of a nuclear war in Europe.
</TEXT>
