<FIRST>r w AM-Iran-Contra-Tapes     05-21 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Contra-Tapes,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Asked to Order Release of Computer Tapes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge is expected to rule soon on
efforts of researchers to gain access to computer tapes that could
shed new light on the Iran-Contra affair and other backstage
dealings in the Reagan White House.
   U.S. District Judge Charles R. Richey has asked for written
arguments by Thursday on whether some decisions by President Bush
to block access to the tapes are subject to court review.
   The government is asking for a summary judgment that would in
effect dismiss the claims of the National Security Archive and
others for access to the computer messages.
   The National Security Archive is a private repository of
government information operated as a division of The Fund for
Peace, a New York non-profit organization.
   Other plaintiffs include the American Historical Association and
American Library Association. They say the tapes contain
information that does not exist anywhere in paper form.
   At issue in the case are backup tapes containing messages sent
on the Professional Office System, known as PROFS, in the National
Security Council and other agencies in the Executive Office of the
President.
   Printouts from the tapes were used by the presidentially
appointed Tower Commission and the congressional Iran-Contra
committees in their investigations of the affair that rocked
President Reagan's second term. They were also introduced as
evidence in the trial of Oliver North, who was convicted of aiding
and abetting in the obstruction of Congress, shredding and altering
documents and accepting a gratuity.
   The plaintiffs say there are more, 144 tapes in a system used by
100 to 150 people on the NSC staff, and 32 in a system used by more
than 300 in the Executive Office of the President, and that such
messages are routinely destroyed.
   ``The fundamental issue in this case is whether the NSC and the
EOP may authorize the routine destruction of information generated
on the PROFS computer systems without complying with the
requirements of the federal records laws,'' attorney Katherine A.
Meyer of Public Citizen Litigation Group, representing the
plaintiffs, told the judge in a memorandum.
   ``Plaintiffs' argument confuses the medium with the message,''
Justice Department attorneys replied. ``PROFS is simply a tool for
conveying information.''
   The government takes the position that the system is a
substitute for calling a colleague on the telephone or talking with
him or her in a hallway.
   The Justice Department told the court that ``the bulk of the
information generated on that system is transitory and does not
constitute record material.'' It said users of the system have been
instructed repeatedly to make a printout of any information that
legally amounts to a government record.
   Ms. Meyer, on the other hand, argued that the NSC and executive
office ``have made a blanket determination that, except in rare
instances, the information generated on the PROFS systems is simply
not covered by any of the federal records laws.''
   If the judge denies the government's motion for summary
judgment, Ms. Meyer said the plaintiffs will file a motion to
obtain additional information they need in order to show that ``the
defendants have violated those laws by routinely deleting and
ultimately deciding to destroy the information that existed on the
PROFS system at the end of the Reagan administration.''
   Defendants in the case include Bush and Donald Wilson, the
archivist of the United States, who the plaintiffs accuse of
``failing to exercise proper oversight of the NSC's and EOP's
routine destruction of information generated on the PROFs system.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
