<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-89 1352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-China-Networks     05-21 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Networks,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime-Time Cliffhanger from China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American television networks continued to report
from Beijing over the weekend, but in most cases without that
important component of television coverage _ pictures.
   ``We're now on the basis of hand-carrying everything out,'' said
CBS' Dan Rather, who left for Tokyo after the network's live
coverage was shut down Friday night in the middle of the season
finale of ``Dallas.''
   What videotape the networks were obtaining was filmed illegally
under martial law, and correspondents were reduced to giving live
reports by telephone. Tension was increasing Sunday as troops were
rumored to be readying a move on the protesters.
   ``There's no question that we're handcuffed by not being able to
broadcast live,'' said CNN anchor Bernard Shaw in a telephone
interview from Beijing, where he remained on Sunday. ``The
government can pull the plug on CNN to keep the story from getting
to the world, but we are not their problem. ... If they don't pull
the telephone plugs, and I expect them to do that, we'll be able to
get word out.''
   Network television coverage had for days brought Americans
inspiring pictures of the remarkable uprising. On Friday, the
government got fed up and ordered coverage to cease. The networks
broke in live to cover that development, ABC even taking its
cameras into CNN's control room in Beijing. ``Dallas'' viewers got
an unexpected, real-life cliffhanger when CBS News broke in with
scenes of Rather attempting to negotiate with Chinese officials.
``I do protest, in the most respectful manner,'' Rather said, to no
avail. He reluctantly signed off one last time as a technician in
the background shut off the satellite dish.
   ``I loved the fella who called in and said, `I was watching Dan
Rather and `Dallas' broke in,''' Rather joked in a telephone
interview from Tokyo on Saturday.
   There were some calls of complaint from ``Dallas'' viewers. But
taking to the air was a matter of being able to broadcast the most
recent CBS News footage _ dramatic scenes of demonstrators being
beaten by police.
   ``The object became to delay it as long as we possibly could,''
Rather said of the halt in coverage. ``China is a society where
authority is everything. That's why I kept asking for something in
writing.''
   Rather's coverage from Tiananmen Square had been shut down
earlier. As he rushed back to the hotel, Lane Venardos, director of
special events, was on the air arguing in a hotel corridor with two
uncomfortable-looking Chinese officials.
   ``The scene in the control room and in the hallway was just
bizarre. I was stalling to get fed everything we had coming in to
us,'' said Venardos, also in Tokyo on Saturday. ``I was using every
ploy I could, including getting them to put it in writing. I knew
he (Rather) was on his way back.''
   Rather said the breakneck ride back to the hotel included a
collision with one of the many bicycles clogging the street, but no
one was hurt.
   Meanwhile, at CNN, Shaw went on live as executive producer Alec
Miran vainly negotiated with Chinese officials.
   ``I certainly was angry,'' Shaw recalled. ``I tried not to show
that on the air. My object was to disgorge the last information we
have. But to have your pencil, your notepad, your microphone and
your camera snatched out of your hands is very disturbing.''
   ``There was frustration, but also a sense of, I don't know if
pride's the right word, but just knowing that what you're doing is
right,'' said Miran, also still in Beijing. ``There were very mixed
emotions, because on one hand, you want to stand up and scream
about freedom of the press. On the other hand, that doesn't mean
anything here.''
   When his arguments at one point had flustered a Chinese
official, Miran recalled, ``he said, `This is China.' In his mind,
that explained everything.''
</TEXT>
