<HEAD>Jewish Group Supports Caravan To Mark Civil Rights Murders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of Reform Judaism gave their
support Sunday to a ``reverse freedom caravan'' planned next month
to mark the 25th anniversary of the murder of three civil rights
workers in Mississippi.
   The board of trustees of the Union of American Hebrew
Congregations, the central body of Reform Judaism in North America,
also called on the movement's 820 synagogues and 1.3 million
members to support the caravan.
   The action is believed to be the first by any Jewish group in
support of the caravan, which will depart from Meridian, Miss., on
June 21 by bus. It will arrive in New York on June 24 after a
stopover in Washington.
   Interdenominational services, rallies and meetings with members
of Congress and other public officials will be held along the way,
culminating with an interfaith program in New York City.
   The caravan will memorialize Andrew Goodman, Michael Schwerner
and James Earl Chaney, three youths who were killed while
participating in a ``Freedom Summer'' project in Philadelphia,
Miss., in 1964.
