<FIRST>r a AM-FatalFire     05-21 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fatal Fire,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emotional Church Service Remembers Family Killed By Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Eenigenburg is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAUK VILLAGE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pastor told a biblical story of
suffering and tragedy Sunday for parishioners, friends and
neighbors grieving for a woman and five of her children, all killed
in a fire.
   David Eenigenburg, pastor of Sauk Village Bible Church, read
from the book of Job, a story of the suffering of a righteous man
struck unexpectedly by tragedy when his seven sons were killed.
   ``The Lord gave, and the Lord hath taken away,'' the passage
reads.
   Tom Ireland, 32, and his 7-year-old daughter Jamie, were the
only survivors of Friday's fire in this suburb south of Chicago.
They were away from home when the fire broke out and killed
Christine Ireland, 27, and her children Nicole, 5; Thomas Jr., 4;
James, 3; Robert, 1{; and Michael, 5 months.
   The family had attended the church for about six months,
Eenigenburg said.
   ``It was a touching service,'' the pastor said in a telephone
interview afterwards. ``There were a lot of tears, and I had a hard
time restraining myself ... when I imagined myself in his shoes.''
   About 200 people, more than usual, packed the church. Many wrote
out checks to help the family, Eenigenburg said.
   ``Jamie has just been overwhelmed with gifts, clothes, that sort
of thing,'' he said. ``I think people are really rising to the
occasion.''
   The funeral home handling services for the victims has
``underwritten all the immediate expenses with the hope they'll be
reimbursed,'' Eenigenburg said.
   Ireland had been laid off all winter from a steel mill and just
started a job at a barrel factory in Blue Island.
   ``He had no benefits coming, certainly no insurance to handle
the cost of the funerals,'' Eeignenburg said.
   Clayton Marcuson, a childhood friend of Christine Ireland, said
he was organizing an all-night fund-raising event for the family
June 24.
   ``She was fun, easy to get along with,'' Marcuson said. ``She
always loved children.''
   The Sauk Village Hall and the Calumet Federal Savings and Loan
in Sauk Village are accepting donations for the family.
   The cause of the blaze, which gutted the family home, was not
determined, but fire investigators said it was accidental and
started in the living room.
</TEXT>
