<FIRST>r a AM-Adams-Tupper     05-21 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Adams-Tupper,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uproar Fades to Silence in Sex-Assault Claim Against Sen. Brock Adams</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington state politics were rocked last
September when a young woman alleged that Sen. Brock Adams had
invited her to his home, drugged her and sexually assaulted her.
   Eight months later, no criminal charges or lawsuits have been
filed. Adams goes on with his legislative work in Washington, D.C.
   The Democratic senator has repeatedly denied the allegations
made by Kari Tupper of Seattle, who said the incident occurred in
March 1987 when she was a secretary on Capitol Hill. Adams, who
served as transportation secretary under President Jimmy Carter,
accused Tupper of demanding $400,000 in ``hush money'' from him.
   Law enforcement authorities said charges were never filed
against Adams because there was a of lack of evidence. Threats of
lawsuits were tossed back and forth between Adams and the Tupper
family, who had been old friends of the senator.
   ``I discussed (the case) with my attorney, and it is very
difficult for a public official who has been a victim of false
statements to take legal action,'' Adams said Thursday in a brief
telephone interview from Washington, D.C. ``I have put the matter
behind me and am moving forward to do my job in the Senate.''
   Adams would not comment on whether the case would affect his
decision on whether to run for re-election in 1992.
   ``I have just put this whole thing behind me and that's all I
have to say. ... I suggest others do the same,'' he said.
   Kari Tupper, now 26, married and a graduate student in English
at the University of Washington, did not return messages relayed
through her mother and on her husband's answering machine at work.
   Her mother, Sylvia Tupper, who once dated Adams, said the case
was on hold, and would not discuss it in detail.
   ``Certain things are being tracked down,'' Mrs. Tupper said.
``The thing is not dead. That's all I can tell you.''
   Karen Marchioro, chair of the state Democrats, said she did not
see that the case had affected Adams politically.
   ``I think he's doing a good job,'' she said. ``The only people I
ever hear mention this are press people.''
</TEXT>
