<FIRST>r i AM-China-HongKong     05-21 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Hong Kong,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>About 400,000 March In Support Of Chinese Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 400,000 people waved banners, listened to
speeches and marched through downtown on Sunday in support of the
pro-democratic movement in China.
   The crowd cut across all economic and age barriers as it tied up
traffic for five hours in this British colony, which is to revert
to Chinese rule in 1997.
   Even staff from the Xinhua News Agency, the unofficial
representative of China in Hong Kong, wrote a banner to support the
pro-democracy marchers who have refused to end their massive
protests in Beijing and other Chinese cities.
   After marching for three hours, the protesters entered a race
track and filled the stands and the field as they listened to
speeches by community leaders, movie stars and lawmakers.
   The rally ended after two and a half hours but a steady flow of
marchers continued to enter the course for two hours. Organizers
estimated the number of protesters at 400,000.
</TEXT>
