<FIRST>r a AM-DrugstoreCowboy     05-21 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugstore Cowboy,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Prepared to Defend Spokesman's Characterization of Gorbachev</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Sunday he was prepared to
defend his press secretary's description of Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev as a ``drugstore cowboy,'' a slang term
suggesting a phony.
   However, French President Francois Mitterrand, appearing at a
joint news conference with Bush, rejected the characterization made
last week by presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater.
   The press spokesman had used the term ``drugstore cowboy'' in
saying that a rash of disarmament offers from Gorbachev were just
part of a public relations campaign.
   ``I think that one must be wary of caricatures,'' Mitterrand
said. ``Mr. Gorbachev is worth very much more than that.''
   Bush then said, ``So much for Marlin. In fairness to the man
...''
   At that point, Fitzwater, standing next to the stage, said,
``No, don't defend me.''
   The president responded, ``No? Don't defend you? Which I would
be perfectly prepared to do.''
   The questioning then turned to another subject.
