<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-89 1710EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Mitterrand     05-21 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mitterrand,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>French President Eschews Characterization as Mediator</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French President Francois Mitterrand expressed
optimism Sunday that differences between the NATO allies over
European short-range nuclear missiles can be reconciled before next
week's NATO summit.
   Mitterrand, appearing at a joint news conference with President
Bush, was asked whether he was acting as an ``intermediary'' or
``conciliator'' in the missiles dispute.
   He replied: ``The only role I play is the role that is my
natural role as a member of the alliance. But I'm not particularly
there to act as a mediator.
   ``Obviously, I'm happy if views can be reconciled and I believe
_ I think that they can be reconciled,'' Mitterrand said. ``I think
that we have now the elements of ideas that could form a decision
that will be taken just in a week's time.''
   He added: ``I think that the decision that will be taken will be
found positive from the point of view of all members of the
alliance.''
   The West German government has been advocating immediate
negotiations with the Soviet Union on short-range nuclear missiles.
But the United States and Britain have balked, saying that Moscow
should first reduce its numerically superior conventional forces.
   Later in the news conference, Mitterrand noted that ``on this
problem, like on other problems, at the outset people have
diverging views, different opinions. But the important thing is to
come to a meeting of the minds and to achieve a common answer. And
this has always been the case in the alliance.''
   The French leader was asked whether the Cold War has now come to
an end.
   Mitterrand replied that ``as far as the Cold War is concerned,
one thing is clear _ and that is that we are moving out of the Cold
War, and the chances are that this will be true for a very long
time. There will be moments when things will be more difficult,
doubtless, but I don't imagine _ I don't see us slipping right back
into the Cold War.''
   He added: ``Of course, anything is possible. A lot will depend
on the trend of developments within the Soviet Union.''
   Mitterrand was asked whether he agreed with recent remarks by
White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater in which the spokesman
described Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev as a ``drugstore
cowboy.''
   Mitterrand replied: ``I think that one must be wary of
caricatures _ Mr. Gorbachev is worth very much more than that.''
   Earlier, the French president had shared commencement speaking
duty with Bush at Boston University. Mitterrand devoted his speech
remarks largely to the environment and said, ``The earth is our
planet, so let us save it.''
   He departed for France in late afternoon.
</TEXT>
