<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-SovietPlane     05-21 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-Soviet Plane,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Discuss Asylum Request of Soviet Pilot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turkish and Soviet officials on Sunday
discussed the asylum request of an air force pilot who fled the
Soviet Union under fire in a MiG-29 fighter jet.
   Capt. Alexander Zuyev requested political asylum in the United
States on Saturday after he fled his country and landed in the
Turkish city of Trabzon.
   A deputy spokesman for the Foreign Ministry, Nazim Belger, said
Zuyev's request for political refuge in the United States ``is
being evaluated under the framework of Turkey's international
obligations and practices.''
   Zuyev, 28, was wounded in the right arm when he was fired on
while taking off from a Soviet airport north of the Black Sea City
of Batumi, said Foreign Ministry spokesman Inal Batu.
   The pilot was operated on and was in good condition at the Black
Sea University Medical School Hospital in Trabzon, Batu told
reporters.
   In a statement carried Sunday by the Anatolia News Agency, the
Turkish General Staff said Turkish radar spotted the MiG-29 and
other Soviet planes in pursuit.
   It said Turkey did not sent any planes to intercept the MiG as
it was about to land and that the Soviet planes chasing it turned
back before entering Turkish airspace.
   The Foreign Ministry said the MiG was flown back to the Soviet
Union Sunday after a group of Soviet technicians who arrived
earlier in the day removed missiles and other weaponry from the
plane.
   The Soviet Union asked Turkish officials to extradite Zuyev,
saying he stole the jet and shot and wounded a sentry guarding the
aircraft at Tskhakaya airfield, the Soviet news agency Tass
reported.
   Belger said Foreign Minister Mesut Yilmaz held talks with Soviet
Ambassador Albert Cernishev on the matter earlier in the day. He
did not elaborate.
   In Washington, a U.S. State Department spokesman said on
Saturday that the United States ``has been in touch with the
Turkish government'' about the case.
</TEXT>
