<FIRST>u i AM-Panama     05-21 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Rallies At Church</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserhoto PAN-3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA CHORRERA, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite an archbishop's exhortation
that churches not be used for political purposes, three opposition
leaders were applauded by the congregation when they attended Mass
Sunday.
   Guillermo Endara, who ran for president in the May 7 election,
and vice presidential candidates Ricardo Arias Calderon and
Guillermo Ford entered the San Francisco church at midmorning to
prolonged applause from about 1,000 worshipers.
   Outside the church more than 100 people waved green and white
flags of the opposition. As Endara entered and left they shouted,
``Justice!'' and ``Endara presidente!''
   Word had circulated since Saturday that the three would attend
Mass in La Chorrera, 18 miles west of Panama City.
   Independent observers of the May 7 election said Endara and
other opposition candidates trounced the government slate lined up
by Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega by a 3-1 margin. Noriega is the
commander of the Panamanian Defense Forces and controls the
government.
   On May 10 the government annulled the elections and also on that
day paramilitary gangs attacked Endara, Ford and Arias with iron
staves.
   Arias Calderon was the candidate for first vice president and
Ford for second vice president.
   Monsignor Marcos McGrath, archbishop of Panama City, issued a
letter on Saturday lamenting political rallies at several churches
last Sunday.
   Panama's Roman Catholic church claims the devotion of a great
majority of the country's 2.5 million citizens. It had been
generally quiet on political and social issues until the election
annulment and the beating of the opposition candidates. It then
spoke out against suppression of ``the popular will.''
   But McGrath said in his letter the church had advised the
opposition of its ``discontent'' with the rallies in churches ``in
the hope that this kind of action will not be repeated.''
   Sunday's Mass was delayed as dozens of journalists gathered
around the front of the altar. The Rev. Jose Luis Andrade, the
parish priest, appealed for ``respect for the sanctity of this
house of God'' and the area was cleared.
   ``These gentlemen (the opposition leaders) are Christians and
can come to Mass here. But we are here to honor God, and this
cannot be converted into a political act,'' he told The Associated
Press before saying Mass.
   The government on Saturday prohibited ``marches, meetings,
public demonstrations or caravans of vehicles'' by any political
organization until at least June 5.
   A government statement said the action was taken because of the
scheduled visit this week by delegates from the Organization of
American States.
   The opposition leaders said the ban was unconstitutional and on
Saturday they were in a motorcade that drove through Panama City
drawing cheering crowds.
   The foreign ministers of Ecuador, Guatemala and Trinidad and
Tobago, accompanied by OAS Secretary-General Joao Baena Soares, are
due in Panama Tuesday to try to help resolve Panama's governmental
crisis.
   The OAS last week approved a resolution that held Noriega
responsible for ``abuses'' and called for ``a transfer of power in
the shortest possible time.''
   Opposition leaders say they will tell the OAS delegation that
results of the May 7 election be recognized and implemented.
   ``The annulment must be annulled,'' Arias Calderon said.
</TEXT>
