<FIRST>r a AM-People-DeKooning     05-21 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-De Kooning,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daughter Asks Court To Declare De Kooning Mentally Incompetent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The daughter of artist Willem de Kooning, who is
said to have Alzheimer's disease, asked a court to declare him
mentally incompetent to manage property worth up to $150 million,
according to ARTnews magazine.
   De Kooning, 85, lives in East Hampton on Long Island, and
continues to paint daily with the violent, slashing strokes that
have earned him fame as one of America's most prominent living
artists.
   His daughter, Lisa, and his attorney, John Eastman, have filed a
petition in state court in Mineola requesting they be named
co-conservators of the artist's assets, which have an estimated
worth of $100 million to $150 million, according to ARTnews' summer
issue.
   Eastman, reached by telephone Sunday at his East Hampton home,
confirmed that the petition was filed in mid-February, but refused
to comment further.
   The battle over representing de Kooning began two years ago when
his longtime dealer, Xavier Fourcade, died, ARTnews said.
   Formal exhibitions and sales of the painter's works were on hold
while offers were considered by his daughter, whose mother is
artist Joan Ward, and de Kooning's wife, Elaine, the magazine said.
   Two weeks after de Kooning's wife died of cancer, his daughter
and Eastman filed the petition.
   The petition said that although the artist ``continues to paint
daily and masterfully ... his physical and mental condition
prevents him from performing everyday tasks and managing his
finances,'' according to ARTnews.
   Dr. Frederick Mortati, a Huntington physician, submitted an
affidavit to the court which said ``it would appear ... Mr. de
Kooning suffers from Alzheimer's disease,'' the magazine said.
   Alzheimer's disease is a progressive, irreversible disorder
whose symptoms include gradual memory loss, impairment of judgment,
disorientation, personality change, difficulty in learning and loss
of language skills.
   The petition said Ms. de Kooning is the sole beneficiary of her
father's will and last year received about $25,000 a month from
him, according to ARTnews.
   Ms. de Kooning, an animal rights activist and amateur sculptor
who is married and has a child, has lived in a house her father
built for her on his property since 1983.
   No date has been set for a hearing on the petition, according to
ARTnews. Court officials were not available for comment Sunday.
   If granted, the petition would give Ms. de Kooning and Eastman
control over the artist's representation and his assets, which
include $7 million in real estate, cash and securities and more
than 300 paintings.
   The average worth of each painting is estimated to be between
$300,000 and $650,000. However, his ``Pink Lady'' sold at a 1988
Sotheby's auction for $3.6 million.
</TEXT>
