<FIRST>r i AM-France-Amnesty     05-21 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Amnesty,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Urges French-Speaking Countries To Stop Abuses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International appealed Monday to the
leaders of French-speaking nations, gathering this week for a
summit in Senegal, to halt widespread human rights abuses in their
countries.
   In a 38-page report issued for the third Francophone Summit,
which opens Wednesday, the human rights organization listed what it
called ``very numerous cases of human rights violations in more
than 30 francophone countries.''
   Included are frequent cases of torture, secret imprisonment,
lengthy detention without trial and bad prison conditions.
   Among the cases cited is that of Salet Gaba, The Associated
Press correspondent in Chad, who has not been heard from since his
arrest in June 1987.
   Last year, Amnesty said it heard Gaba had died after being
mistreated in prison, and it called for a government inquiry. There
has been no response from President Hissene Habre's government.
   About 40 countries in which French is spoken _ ranging from
Canada to Haiti to Madagascar to Vietnam _ are expected to attend
the Dakar meeting.
   The countries criticized by Amnesty include two that refuse to
attend meetings of the group: Algeria and Syria.
   While most of the accusations of human rights abuses were
directed at former French colonies in Africa, even France and
Switzerland did not escape criticism.
   The Swiss were criticized for refusing to allow conscientious
objectors to perform civilian service as an alternative to their
draft duty, and the French for requiring objectors to serve two
years of alternative service, compared with just one year for army
draftees.
</TEXT>
