<HEAD>U.S. Professor Is Spokesman For Noriega</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `The Panama...,' to CORRECT that Panama treaties
`went into effect' in 1979, sted `were signed.' They were signed in 1977.</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A professor on paid sabbatical from Brooklyn
College has become the main North American spokesman for Panamanian
strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, a newspaper reported Sunday.
   Carlos Russell has appeared on radio and U.S. network television
as a spokesman for Noriega, the commander of the Panamanian Defense
Forces and de facto ruler of Panama, the Daily News reported.
   Russell, 54, a professor of educational services and a native of
Panama, also serves as Panama's alternate representative to the
Organization of American States.
   A college spokesman, Barry Rosen, told the News that Russell was
awarded a one-year fellowship leave at $30,000 _ half his usual pay
_ last August. Russell said he has asked the college to extend his
leave for another year.
   He told the college, part of the City University, that he would
use the fellowship to ``increase knowledge in the culture and
politics of West Indians with particular emphasis on Panama.''
   Russell said he became Panama's alternate OAS representative
``four or five months ago'' and receives $3,000 monthly in salary
and expenses from that country.
   Rosen said the college was enquiring to see if Russell's status
had changed since he became a Noriega representative.
   In a telephone interview Sunday, Russell said the United States
has ``a fixation on Noriega.''
   ``If they have a fixation on him they do not have to discuss or
question the real reason why the United States is in Panama _ to
attempt to retain control of the Panama Canal after the year
2000,'' he said.
   The Panama treaties, which went into effect in 1979, are to give
Panama sovereignty over the canal and several American military
bases by the end of the century.
   Russell claimed that opponents of Noriega were responsible for
voting irregularities in the recent general election. ``American
money was used by the opposition to defraud the election,'' he said.
   Independent monitors say the opposition won the May 7
presidential election by an overwhelming margin, despite tampering
by Noriega's forces. A government-appointed election tribunal
nullified the election.
   Among his other activities, Russell led a series of tours of
Uganda by journalists and educators in the 1970s and wrote a series
of articles in the Amsterdam News, a New York City newspaper,
casting Ugandan dictator Idi Amin in a favorable light.
</TEXT>
