<FIRST>r a AM-Bush'sSister     05-21 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush's Sister,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Bush's Sister Suffers Mishap on Way to Graduation Ceremony</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's sister was on her way to hear her
brother speak at Boston University's commencement Sunday when she
accidentally struck three police officers with her car, causing
minor injuries.
   The officers had been directing Nancy Bush Ellis to a parking
area near the campus where 30,000 graduates and their families
gathered to hear Bush and French President Francois Mitterrand
deliver the keynote address.
   Investigating officers reported there was no apparent negligence
on the part of Mrs. Ellis and no charges were filed, said police
spokeswoman Linda Orlando.
   Mrs. Ellis, a resident of Lincoln, stopped to talk to the
officers after she encountered a roadblock.
   She then put the car in reverse and the car suddenly lurched
backwards, knocking the officers down.
   ``One officer was hit in the knee with the car's fender, another
was hit by the door as it flung open and a third was swept back
about 10 feet by the door itself,'' Orlando said.
   She said Mrs. Ellis' Audi sedan then bashed into an police truck
stationed at the roadblock. ``That's what stopped the vehicle,''
Orlando said.
   Two of the officers had minor cuts and bruises and the one who
was swept back 10 feet suffered minor head and neck injuries,
Orlando said. All three were treated at a hospital and released.
   ``All's well that ends well, so to speak,'' Orlando said.
   There was no immediate from Mrs. Ellis; she did not return a
message left on the answering machine at her home in the Boston
suburb.
</TEXT>
