<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-89 1857EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-ArabSummit     05-21 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arab Summit,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egypt Welcomed Back to Arab Fold</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CASABLANCA, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt was officially welcomed back to
the Arab fold, after an absence of 10 years, as the Arab League
opened a ministerial meeting Sunday to prepare for a summit
conference.
   Moroccan Foreign Minister Abdel-Latif Filali, in the opening
address, said, ``We are all witnessing today an important
historical event demonstrated in the participation of the Arab
Republic of Egypt's delegation ... in our meetings after a long
absence.''
   Two seats for delegates from the 22-nation Arab League were
vacant at the conference hall.
   Libya is boycotting the session because it opposes Egypt's
return to the league, and there was no representative from Lebanon,
where there are rival Christian and Moslem governments.
   Egypt's membership was suspended after former President Anwar
Sadat signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1979.
   ``I am certain that Egypt's return to the Arab League and the
resumption of its full membership in our organization will
contribute to joint Arab action and the strengthening of Arab
solidarity,'' Filali said.
   Egyptian Foreign Minister Ismat Abdel-Meguid said in response:
``Egypt is pleased to resume its membership and the historical and
important responsibilities that entails.
   ``It also stresses it shall fulfill its duties in accordance
with the Arab League charter.''
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak is expected to attend the
summit conference that opens Tuesday.
   The ministerial meeting began at 7 p.m. after several delays
because of a six-member committee discussion of the situation in
Lebanon, where Christian militias have been waging artillery duels
with Syrian army units and their Druse allies.
   The committee did not submit a report but agreed to recommend to
the Arab leaders that both of Lebanon's declared prime ministers,
Christian Michel Aoun and Moslem Salim Hoss, be invited to the
summit.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, ``voiced reservations''
about the proposal to invite Gen. Aoun who has vowed to dislodge
Syrian forces from Lebanon, according to conference sources who
spoke with the condition they not be identified.
   Lebanon and the Palestinian uprising in the Israeli occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip will be two of the main topics at the
summit.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization is expected to complain
that it has not received the aid promised at the last Arab summit
in Algeria in June 1988.
   PLO officials say league members promised to give the
organization a $128 million one-time payment and then $43 million
per month.
   They said only Saudi Arabia and Libya contributed to the
one-time payment, with the Saudis providing $28 million and Libya
$12 million.
   They also said the PLO has received only $12 million in promised
monthly allocations.
</TEXT>
