<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Kidnap     05-21 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Kidnap,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three West German Relief Workers Leave Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three West Germans working for the
ASME-Humanitas relief organization left Lebanon Sunday, six days
after two colleagues were reported kidnapped in this southern port
city.
   A police spokesman said the three boarded the Lebanese cargo
ship Libra in Sidon and it departed for Cyprus at 5 p.m.
   Markus Quint, 21, who was reported abducted May 4 and returned
safely to the group on May 14, was one of the three. The others
were not identified.
   Quint was reported kidnapped with Petra Schnitzler, a nurse, and
Heinrich Struebig, an administrator. Ms. Schnitzler and Struebig
were released in a few hours but Quint was held until May 14.
   On May 16, Ms. Schnitzler, Struebig and Thomas Kemptner, 28,
were seized by gunmen in Sidon.
   Ms. Schnitzler was freed a few hours later by local militiamen
looking for thieves who stopped the abductors' car.
   Struebig and Kemptner are still missing. There have been no
claims of responsibility for the reported kidnappings, and Quint
and Ms. Schnitzler have refused to identify their abductors or
provide other details.
   Ms. Schnitzler, 26, told reporters she would stay in Lebanon
until Struebig and Kemptner were freed. Another woman working for
ASME-Humanitas also remained in Lebanon.
   The Germans have been staying since Thursday in two bases their
organization maintains in Zahrani and Aaqbiyeh, six miles south of
Sidon and controlled by the Shiite Amal militia.
   The Germans were expelled on Thursday from their main base at
the Mieh Mieh Palestinian refugee camp by the Palestine Liberation
Organization, which accused them of concealing the identities of
those involved in the kidnappings and of ignoring security
regulations.
   At least 15 other foreigners are being held hostage in Lebanon,
including nine Americans. Longest held is Terry Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press, who was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   In addition an elderly Briton, Jack Mann, disappeared on May 12
in Beirut, and it is believed he was kidnapped.
</TEXT>
