<HEAD>Marcos Remains In Very Critical Condition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Sunday medical briefing, hospital
spokesman clarifying that Marcos not improving but in `upswing mode.' Picks
up 4th graf pvs, `Marcos' wife...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferdinand Marcos remained in very critical
condition Sunday, and his doctors said the former Philippines
president was alert and responding to medication.
   Marcos, 71, is undergoing kidney dialysis, has a respirator to
help him breath and is hooked up to a monitoring system, said
Eugene Tiwanak, assistant adminstrator of St. Francis Medical
Center.
   Marcos is alert and conscious and seems to be responding to
medication to fight a bacterial infection, said Tiwanak, who
stressed this didn't mean there has been any improvement in Marcos'
condition.
   ``His condition is episodic _ up and down. He's still in the
upswing mode,'' Tiwanak said at what was to be the only scheduled
medical briefing Sunday.
   On Saturday, Marcos was more alert and was able to communicate
with doctors through hand signals, Tiwanak said.
   Marcos' wife, Imelda, meanwhile, denounced statements attributed
to Marcos supporters during a rally in Manila on Saturday that
Americans would be killed if Marcos dies in exile.
   The statement might have been the work of radicals infiltrating
Marcos supporters and attempting to provoke a violent reaction to
Philippines President Corazon Aquino's announcement that Marcos
will not be allowed to return, even if he dies, Mrs. Marcos said.
   ``It was precisely to bring about a reconciliation and to avoid
a continuation of this division that, transcending my own pain and
hurt, I appealed to Madame Aquino to allow Marcos to return to die
in his homeland,'' she said.
   ``I don't want violence, and I'm afraid that the hard-line
statements of the madame (Aquino) have caused this emotional
reaction among some people,'' she said.
   The Philippine Supreme Court on Friday denied the Marcoses'
petition to force the government to allow their return.
   ``We are being kicked back and forth like a football, and the
United States is being made into the fall guy,'' Mrs. Marcos said.
   During a convention in Manila of a revived opposition party,
Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile, who played a key role in the revolt against
Marcos, said Sunday that Mrs. Aquino should display leadership by
allowing Marcos to return to die in his homeland.
   Enrile, who was named secretary-general of the Nationalista
Party, said ``there is no reason why he should be deprived of his
right to come home at this time of his life. He's so ill. How can
he destabilize the country?''
</TEXT>
