<FIRST>u a AM-NavigationSatellite     05-21 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navigation Satellite,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Satellite Launch Postponed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge thunderstorm forced the Air
Force to postpone the launch of an advanced navigation satellite
for a second time Sunday night.
   The launch was rescheduled for Tuesday at 7:43 p.m. Officials
decided to stand down 48 hours because Monday's weather forecast
was not favorable and the launch team needed a rest period, said
Lt. Col. Ron Rand, the Air Force launch commentator.
   ``The weather is bad and getting worse,'' Rand said. ``There is
a thunderstorm, an anvil cloud and lightning within five miles of
the launch pad. The lightning requires a shutdown of the rocket
guidance computer.''
   As he spoke, a huge black cloud rolled over Cape Canaveral from
the northwest, rain poured down and lightning crackled over the
area.
   The postponement was announced 40 minutes before the planned
liftoff of the Delta 2 rocket at 7:51 p.m.
   The launch was first postponed Saturday night because of strong
winds above the launch pad. The countdown clock then stood at 4
minutes.
   The Delta 2 carries a $65 million Navstar satellite that will
enable military units such as ships, planes, submarines and tanks
to determine their location within 50 feet and in some cases to
within 10 feet anywhere around the globe.
</TEXT>
