<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     05-21 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report 150 Killed in Tribal Fighting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 150 people have been killed in
fighting over land ownership and grazing areas in Sudan's western
Darfar region, Khartoum newspapers reported Sunday.
   The English-language Sudan Times said the fighting began Friday
when about 3,000 Arabs attacked members of the African Fur tribe in
the vicinity of Jabal Mara Mountain.
   Interior Minister Mubarak Fadil Mahdi went to the region Sunday
to try to stop the fighting. The Information Ministry declined
comment on the newspaper accounts, saying a report would be issued
when it received information from Mahdi.
   There was no indication the Darfar fighting is linked to the
civil war in southern Sudan that has claimed thousands of lives
since 1983. Most of the rebels in the south are Christians or
animists who want greater automony from the predominantly
Arab-Moslem government in Khartoum.
   A train carrying 1,500 tons of food and other relief supplies
was en route Sunday to southern Sudan as part of a project to avoid
a repeat of last year's disaster, when up to 500,000 people died of
starvation and disease in villages isolated by the war.
   The train left Muglad in southwestern Sudan on Saturday for the
southern cities of Malwal, Maput and Aweil. Malwal and Maput are
controlled by the rebels' Sudan People's Liberation Army and the
government holds Aweil.
   Operation Lifeline Sudan is operating the relief project. It is
part of a U.N. effort to send 100,000 tons of food to southern
Sudan.
   U.N. officials say starvation threatens at least 100,000 people.
</TEXT>
