<FIRST>r a AM-Eastern-Florida     05-21 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Florida,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida's Pension Fun May Have Role in Eastern Buyout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bob Martinez may try to use
Florida's $17 billion pension fund to back the purchase of Eastern
Airlines in an effort to protect jobs provided by the Miami-based
airline, according to reports Sunday.
   Two newspapers, The Miami Herald and the Palm Beach Post,
reported that an investment of at least $50 million was being
considered, given the proper guarantees against loss.
   Two high-ranking state aides were in New York Friday for talks
with officials of Eastern Airlines' pilot union and financial and
legal consultants.
   One of them, Brian Ballard, Martinez' chief of operations,
confirmed the negotiations.
   Martinez ``is extremely interested in protecting Floridians'
jobs'' and wants to keep Eastern in one piece and in Florida, ``but
we'll do nothing that wouldn't be an outstanding investment for
(Florida's) pension holders.''
   The loan was proposed by the Air Line Pilots Association, whose
support of striking Machinists has kept the Miami-based airline
virtually grounded since March 4.
   ``We propose to to give them a very secure investment for the
pension plan, and get Eastern back,'' said Randolph Babbitt,
executive administrator of ALPA.
   At the time the strike began, Eastern employed about 30,000
workers, 12,000 of them in Florida.
   The unions were seeking the financial help as part of
negotiations between the airline unions and two potential buyers:
Chicago commodities trader Joseph Ritchie and former Piedmont
Aviation Inc. President William Howard.
   An Eastern spokesman scoffed at the investment idea Saturday.
   ``The Ritchie and Howard proposals can best be described as
humpty-dumpty,'' Robin Matell said. ``Neither one is economically
realistic. If the state chooses to invest its money that way, it
will probably be the fastest method on record to find out whether
pensioners can survive on Social Security checks alone.''
   Details of the offers from Ritchie and Howard have been
unavailable, but both reportedly call for $210 million in wage
concessions in each of the next five years in exchange for partial
ownership.
   A representative of Howard's investor group said its bid
included $725 million in new capital, although only a small part
would be cash.
   To complete the deal and satisfy a federal bankruptcy judge in
New York who must approve the sale, the unions would need to raise
at least $50 million more, Babbitt said. Searching for the balance,
union officials approached the state and other pension funds,
Babbitt said.
   To guarantee the state money, the unions would agree to place 1
percent of the airline's labor payroll in an escrow account as
insurance that the state would receive a return on the investment.
   ``Labor can guarantee that money if for any reason the company
was unable to pay dividends for the state's investment,'' Babbitt
said.
   Cliff Hinkle, executive director of the state Board of
Administration who traveled to New York with Ballard, refused to
discuss specifics, but noted that ``we look at investment
possibilities every day.''
   Florida's pension fund is one of the healthiest in the nation,
containing about $17 billion in a diverse portfolio of common
stocks, bonds and real estate. It is the 12th largest in the United
States and 25th largest in the world, Hinkle said.
   As governor, Martinez sits at the head of the state's
three-member Board of Administration, which oversees state
investments.
   Eastern has been under Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection since
March 9. Any sale must be approved by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton
Lifland, who on Monday will receive a report on the offers by
Howard and Ritchie and consider developer Donald Trump's offer to
buy the airlines' shuttle service between Boston, New York and
Washington.
   Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern parent company Texas Air
Corp., has proposed selling $1.8 billion in assets to restructure
the airline into a smaller operation.
   In addition to Trump's $365 million offer for the shuttle,
Phoenix-based America West Airlines has made a $751-million bid for
the shuttle and 15 Boeing 757s. USAir has offered $525 million for
15 Boeing 757s, maintenance hangers and airport landing slots in 10
cities.
</TEXT>
