<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Politics     05-21 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Politics,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Party Formed, Laurel At Head, Urges Marcos Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A revived opposition party urged
President Corazon Aquino Sunday to call new elections, and the
group's new secretary-general said the president should allow
Ferdinand Marcos to return as a sign of her leadership.
   The call came at the end of a one-day convention of the
Nationalista Party. The 4,000 delegates agreed to revive the party
as the major opposition movement against Mrs. Aquino.
   Vice President Salvador Laurel was named party president, Sen.
Juan Ponce Enrile was designated secretary-general and Blas Ople, a
labor minister under Marcos, was chosen executive vice president,
both by acclamation.
   Laurel quit as foreign secretary on September 1987 and refused
to serve in the Cabinet, claiming ``fundamental differences'' with
Mrs. Aquino. Laurel remains as vice president, which is an elective
post.
   During the convention, Enrile, a former defense minister, said
Mrs. Aquino should display leadership by allowing Marcos to return
from Hawaii to die in his homeland.
   ``We believe that Marcos should be allowed to come back,''
Enrile said. ``There is no reason why he should be deprived of his
right to come home at this time of his life. He's so ill. How can
he destabilize the country?''
   The former president was reported in critical condition Sunday
in a Honolulu hospital after undergoing emergency kidney surgery.
Hospital officials said his prognosis is poor, although he showed
signs of responding to treatment.
   On Friday, Mrs. Aquino refused to allow Marcos to return and
said her government would not allow him to buried in the
Philippines. Marcos has lived in Hawaii since he was ousted in a
popular uprising in February 1986 that propelled Mrs. Aquino to
power.
   Mrs. Aquino has cited national security for refusing previous
bids by Marcos to come home.
   ``If Mrs. Aquino feels she is the leader of the country, then
she should show that she is, by controlling the situation where her
worst perceived enemy is inside the country, not when he is outside
and dying,'' Enrile said.
   Enrile played a key role in a military revolt against Marcos,
which triggered the ``people power'' uprising that toppled the
former president. Mrs. Aquino retained Enrile as defense chief but
fired him in November 1986 after a coup attempt by his followers.
   Sunday's convention was the latest attempt to put together a
unified, viable opposition to Mrs. Aquino.
   Previous attempts to build an opposition party have foundered
because of personal rivalries and the fact that many leading
figures are tainted by their previous links to Marcos.
   The Nacionalistas, who suspended activities when Marcos declared
eight years of martial rule in 1972, hope to win the presidency in
1992, when Mrs. Aquino's term expires. She has said she will not
seek re-election.
</TEXT>
