<FIRST>r a AM-Non-FallingTower     05-21 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Non-Falling Tower,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Building Targeted for Demolition, But Won't Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-rise building wracked by two
demolition blasts leaned precariously but did not fall Sunday,
prompting officials to evacuate nearby residents while wrecking
crews moved in with a crane.
   ``We've got one building leaning and one building leaning
against it,'' said police Major John Power. ``It's a hazardous
condition and I don't know what could happen.''
   A cloud of smoke rose from the bottom of the building around
8:30 a.m., but the 10-story tower remained standing. Patrolman John
Egan said demolition crews were not sure why the implosion did not
work.
   The demolition experts, who had used 500 pounds of dynamite in
the first implosion, fetched 36 pounds of more explosives and
staged a second effort. This time, part of the building tipped
slightly and leaned against another tower that may also face
demolition, but the structure remained standing.
   A ball and crane were at the scene, but officials said
demolition plans still had to be made. Stephen O'Rourke, head of
the city's housing authority, said it could take up to two weeks
for the wrecking crews to dismantle the listing building.
   Police had warned people to watch the second try from home on
their televisions after officers had problems with crowding at the
site.
   Three streets were partially cordoned off for the night. Power
said a few families living nearby would have to find somewhere else
to stay until the building was brought down. Residents without a
place to go would be accommodated, officials said.
   The two towers and one other are the subject of a federal
lawsuit filed by Project BASIC, a housing advocacy group, against
the Providence Housing Authority.
   U.S. District Judge Raymond Pettine allowed the tower to be
demolished after architects ruled that the building, when being
prepared for demolition, was made unsafe.
   But Pettine's April 21 temporary restraining order against
demolition still stands for the two other towers. Project BASIC
contends the buildings are structurally safe and should be
preserved because of the need for low-income housing.
   The housing authority had planned to build smaller residential
buildings at the site.
</TEXT>
