<FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-89 2258EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     05-21 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Call for Political Rehabilitation of Executed Premier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SZEGED, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 400 delegates demanding reforms in
the ruling Communist Party called Sunday for the political
rehabilitation of Premier Imre Nagy, executed after the 1956
revolution.
   The two-day session, which ended Sunday, was the first national
conference of the reform movement. It followed a meeting in
Kecskemet on April 15 when Communist Party members urged major
changes in Hungary's political structure.
   In a final resolution, the delegates representing 110 working
groups from throughout Hungary said an official declaration should
be issued rehabilitating Nagy and state that he was the victim of a
``rigged political trial.''
   Conference delegates reviewed the 40 years of Communist rule
after World War II and declared:
   _A special congress of the Communist Party should be held next
fall, ahead of the session scheduled in 1990, ``to clear all
political issues as to where the party is going.''
   _Representatives to the congress should be elected at local
levels.
   _The party should reject ``democratic centralism'' _ the
principle that the minority should accept all decisions adopted by
the majority.
   _The Communist Party should change its name to Hungarian
Socialist Party, Democratic Socialist People's Party or the
Hungarian Reform Party ``to reflect its new, democratic character.''
   But the issue of the rehabilitation of Nagy, the premier when
the Soviets sent troops into Hungary to crush a revolt, was the
most emotional issue.
   The resolution said the rehabilitation should be declared before
the June 16 reburial of Nagy's remains.
   The burial ceremony is to be broadcast by state television but
the government has no plans to be officially represented.
   Nagy, who formed a coalition government in 1956 that tried to
break with the Soviet Union and Warsaw pact, and others convicted
of revolutionary activities were executed on June 16, 1958. Their
bodies were buried in unmarked graves.
   Earlier this year the government, under intense pressure, agreed
to reburial of the bodies and the funeral.
   A government commission is reviewing Nagy's trial.
   Imre Pozsgay, a reform member of the Communist Party's
Politburo, told a news conference Saturday the impatience of
reformers for a quick decision on Naby's rehabilitation was
justified. But he said he would wait until the public prosecutor
files a final report, expected sometime this fall.
   ``Execution for political reasons cannot be justified under any
circumstances,'' he said.
</TEXT>
