<FIRST>r a AM-CommencementRdp     05-21 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commencement Rdp,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Mitterrand, Ueberroth Speak at College Commencements</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-China</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BXA2,4,10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN W. OATIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush expressed hope for world peace, French President
Francois Mitterrand stressed environmentalism and ex-baseball
commissioner Peter Ueberroth pushed volunteerism in commencement
speeches around the nation Sunday.
   Also speaking at college graduation ceremonies were U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, novelist E.L. Doctorow,
U.S. Environmental Protection Administration chief William K.
Reilly and Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo.
   Boston University scored a commencement coup with speeches by
both Bush and Mitterrand, who appeared before 31,000 graduating
seniors, relatives and friends at Nickerson Field football stadium
under mostly sunny skies.
   Bush said he was optimistic about the prospects for continued
peace, particularly in Western Europe, but cautioned ``the history
of this century teaches Americans and Europeans to remain
prepared.''
   Bush, who faces pressure for further disarmament in Europe,
stressed NATO's importance and urged cooperative efforts to
preserve its strength.
   Mitterrand, who joined Bush on the dais, devoted his remarks
largely to the environment. ``The Earth is our planet, so let us
save it,'' he said.
   Bush received a standing ovation. But Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis, his defeated rival for the presidency, drew louder
applause from the hometown audience when he was introduced on the
stage.
   Bush and Mitterrand received honorary doctor of laws degrees.
Bush's wife, Barbara, was awarded an honorary doctorate in humane
letters.
   At the University of Notre Dame, Ueberroth told more than 2,300
graduates that volunteerism is a ``hidden asset'' that can be the
best investment a person makes in life.
   ``I encourage everybody here, when you find yourself in a
profession, from the very first day, volunteer,'' said Ueberroth,
who received an honorary doctor of laws degree.
   Doctorow, the author of ``World's Fair'' and other novels, also
advocated volunteerism at Brandeis University's commencement for
700 graduates.
   Among those receiving honorary degrees were New York Times
caricaturist Al Hirschfeld, AIDS researcher Mathilde Krim, New
Republic Editor-in-Chief and alumnus Martin Peretz and pianist
Andre Watts.
   Perez de Cuellar, appearing at Tufts University in Medford,
Mass., near Boston, urged 2,000 graduating seniors to join him in
working for greater world harmony.
   ``All over the world there is now a strong feeling that
international relations have turned a corner and that we are
entering a new era of cooperation among nations,'' he said. ``Even
those who were formerly disheartened are saying that international
conflicts seem to be on their way to solution.''
   In addition to the secretary-general, honorary degrees were
awarded to Academy Award-winning director Bernardo Bertolucci,
Argentine Foreign Minister Dante Caputo and British astrophysicist
and author Stephen Hawking.
   In Providence, R.I., the EPA's top official urged nearly 1,000
Providence College graduates to join a new worldwide commitment to
saving the environment.
   ``We have to invent new ways of managing our relationship with
our environment, going far beyond what we have accomplished during
the last two decades,'' Reilly said.
   ``Increasingly, the world's great cities are choking in
pollution, awash in waste, clogged with automobiles, their rivers
open sewers,'' said Reilly, who received an honorary degree.
   Schroeder, who also picked up an honorary diploma, urged civic
and national pride on about 500 graduates and undergraduates at
Simmons College, a small liberal arts school for women in Boston.
   ``The 1980s has been a decade where the trilogy was me, myself
and I,'' said Schroeder. ``We've got to start thinking about us,
our community, our country and how we are going to compete. There's
never been a time when our country needed you more.''
</TEXT>
