<FIRST>u i AM-Argentina 1stLd-Writethru   05-21 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0762,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Alfonsin and Menen Consider Early Transfer of Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Alfonsin agreement to move
up inauguration; pickup 5th graf, `Menem, the ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Raul Alfonsin agreed
Sunday to move up the scheduled Dec. 10 inauguration of
President-elect Carlos Menem because of Argentina's economic crisis.
   But Alfonsin, in a statement, said no date was set after he and
Menem held a daylong meeting with aides.
   The Central Bank meanwhile ordered all banks and foreign
exchange houses closed Monday while the government prepared a new
economic plan that will include price controls and export taxes.
   ``I have said and I repeat, I am not going to flee any
responsibility,'' Alfonsin said late Sunday in a statement read to
reporters by press secretary Jose Ignacio Lopez.
   ``Nevertheless, I note that in the context of a severe economic
crisis, the period of transition is too long,'' Alfonsin said after
meeting with his Cabinet.
   Menem, the Peronist Party leader who won the May 14 presidential
election, told the newspaper Clarin in an interview published
Sunday that he would take office early ``if there is a general
consensus of our entire community.'' He said that would include
business, labor and political groups, the armed forces and leaders
of the the Roman Catholic church.
   In the elections earlier this month the Peronists also won
virtual contol of both houses of Congress.
   Alfonsin's inauguration in December 1983, following elections
that October, ended nearly eight years of military dictatorships.
He was barred by the constitution from seeking a second term.
   Menem defeated Eduardo Angeloz, the Radical Civic Union
candidate.
   Sources in both parties, speaking with the condition they not be
identified, said discussions were being held on how to move up
Menem's inauguration without violating the constitution and if the
new Congress also should be sworn in early.
   Peronist Congressman Eduardo Bauza said Sunday his party is
demanding that Alfonsin's economic team resign. ``They are in great
measure responsible for this crisis,'' he said.
   Bauza also said the transfer of power could be held July 9,
Argentina's independence day. Bauza is considered to be a contender
for finance minister in a Peronist administration.
   The economic situation is putting pressure on both parties.
   Interest has not been paid since last year on the country's $59
billion foreign debt. Menem has said the Central Bank has only $300
million in reserves.
   Economists say the banking system is in jeopardy. They say about
$170 million in bonds fall due this week and banks could have
trouble raising the money.
</TEXT>
